9950502_orientale-lumen.html ''Orientale Lumen''] \u2013 Apostolic Letter of Pope John Paul II on the Eastern Churches, 1995\n* [http://w2.vatican.va/content/benedict-xvi/en/speeches/2006/november/documents/hf_ben-xvi_spe_20061130_dichiarazione-comune.html Common Declaration of Pope Benedict XVI and the Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew I, 2006]\n\n{{-}}\n{{Eastern Orthodox Church footer}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Africa topic|Eastern Orthodoxy in}}\n{{Asia topic|Eastern Orthodoxy in}}\n{{Europe topic|Eastern Orthodoxy in}}\n{{Patriarchs of Constantinople}}\n{{Pentarchy}}\n{{Eastern Christianity footer}}\n{{Ecumenical councils}}\n{{Christianity footer}}\n{{Religion topics}}\n}}\n\n{{Subject bar |commons = y |q = y |commons-search = Orthodox Church |s = Eastern Orthodox Church |s-search = Eastern Orthodox Church |wikt = y |wikt-search = Eastern Orthodox Church |portal1 = Bible |portal2 = Christianity |portal3 = Religion |portal4= Saints}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox Church| ]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in the 1st century]]\n", "name_user": "SrpskiAnonimac", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eChurch calendar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eastern_Orthodox_Church"}
{"title_page": "Bryony Kimmings", "text_new": "'''Bryony Kimmings''' (born 30 March 1981){{cn|date=July 2018}} is a British live artist based in [[London]] and [[Cambridgeshire]]. She is an associate artist of the [[Soho Theatre]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sohotheatre.com/writers/writers/bryony-kimmings/ | title=Bryony Kimmings | publisher=Soho Theatre Company Ltd | accessdate=18 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618200319/http://www.sohotheatre.com/writers/writers/bryony-kimmings/|archivedate=18 June 2016}}</ref> and, in 2016, was commissioned to write ''The Pacifist's Guide to the War on Cancer'' for [[Complicite]] Associates.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.complicite.org/productions/APacifistsGuideToTheWarOnCancer | title=A Pacifist's Guide to the War on Cancer | publisher=Complicite | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe creates multi-platform art works to provoke change.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://theweekendedition.com.au/the-locals/bryony-kimmings/ | title=Bryony Kimmings, performance artist, Fake It \u2019Til You Make It |first= Chrisanthi |last=Demos|work=The Weekend Edition |date=18 June 2015 | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> Her work centres mostly around \"social experiments\",<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/magazine/archive/2014/06/play/bryony-kimmings |title=Bryony Kimmings explores link between drinking with creativity |first=Madhumita |last=Venkataramanan |magazine=Wired |department=Neuroscience |date=June 2014 |accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> which in the past have included the artist retracing an [[Sexually transmitted infection|STI]] to its source,<ref name=TM>{{cite web | url=http://themusic.com.au/interviews/all/2014/03/26/bryony-kimmings/24747/ | title=Arts Interview Bryony Kimmings | publisher=Street Press Australia Pty Ltd |date= 26 March 2014|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> spending seven days in a controlled environment in a constant state of intoxication<ref name=7Day>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/aug/19/7-day-drunk-review | title=7 Day Drunk \u2013 review |first=Lyn|last= Gardner| newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |date=20 August 2011| accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> and becoming a pop star invented by a nine-year-old.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/aug/06/female-role-models-bryony-kimmings | title=Lack of female role models? Make one up: Bryony Kimmings' homemade hero |first=Catherine|last=Love| newspaper=The Guardian |date= 7 August 2013| accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs well as appearing at the Soho Theatre, Kimmings' work has toured across the world including: The Southbank Centre<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.southbankcentre.co.uk/node/20860|title=Southbank Centre {{!}}|website=Southbank Centre|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>, BAC Grandhall, [[Antifest]] (Finland), Culturgest (Portugal), Fusebox Festival (Texas), [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]] (Australia), and Lisinski Operahouse (Croatia).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/about.html | title=Bryony Kimmings | publisher=Bryony Kimmings | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nKimmings graduated with a degree in Modern Drama from [[Brunel University]] in 2003.<ref name=\"BKInt\">{{cite web | url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/comedy/bryony-kimmings-interview-joke-therapy-10426133.html | title=Bryony Kimmings interview: Joke therapy | newspaper=Evening Standard |first=Bruce|last=Dessau|date= 30 July 2015|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> In a 2011 interview she said of her time at Brunel: \"It was Live Art and the history of performance artists that excited me the most\", and so immediately afterwards she established the company 'Glass Eyed' with friends. 'Glass Eyed' created work for two years before being dissolved.<ref name=\"RR\">{{cite web | url=http://www.run-riot.com/articles/blogs/interview-bryony-kimmings-talks-sex-booze-and-performance | title=Interview: Bryony Kimmings Talks Sex, Booze and Performance | publisher=RunRiot.com | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 she began ''Celebrityville'' a soap cabaret following the lives of forgotten celebrities living in a fictional town. A new episode was created every month between 2006 and 2008. Describing working on ''Celebrityville'' Kimmings said \"this gave me a baptism of fire really, making such a large volume of work, learning about how to run a night, what to do if things broke half way through, making costumes, doing marketing - everything.\"<ref name=RR/> When ''Celebrityville'' ended, Kimmings began to explore a solo live art career with autobiographical themes.<ref name=RR/>\n\n==Shows==\n\n=== Performance work ===\n* ''I'm a Phoenix, Bitch'' (2018). Premiered at the [[Battersea Arts Centre]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/bryony-kimmings-im-a-phoenix-bitch-battersea_48085.html|title=Bryony Kimmings' I'm a Phoenix, Bitch to return to Battersea Arts Centre in 2019 {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> This piece can be viewed as a subversive feminist musical piece, with elements of a pop-video, horror film, art installation and therapy session. This piece comes from a deeply personal place for Kimmings, taking inspiration from a moment in 2015 when she broke up with her boyfriend, lost her mind and nearly lost her baby.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/oct/09/im-a-phoenix-bitch-review-bryony-kimmings|title=I\u2019m a Phoenix, Bitch review \u2013 wacky, warped and wonderful|last=Gillinson|first=Miriam|date=2018-10-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2016, Kimmings nearly drowning, followed by post-natal breakdowns, an imploding relationship and an extremely sick child that left her feeling overwhelmed with life. Four years later, she is able to deal with her life again, but she is wearing the scars of that year like having a weight on her shoulders. It provokes the questions of: Who do we become after trauma? How do we turn pain into power? How do we fly instead of drown?<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://homemcr.org/production/im-a-phoenix-bitch/|title=I'm a Phoenix, Bitch|website=HOME|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*''Fake it \u2018til you Make it'' (2015). Premiered at the [[Traverse Theatre]], Edinburgh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/aug/08/fake-it-til-you-make-it-edinburgh-festival-review-traverse-bryony-kimmings-tim-grayburn-depression|title=Fake It 'Til You Make It at Edinburgh festival review \u2013 divides audience into smilers and sobbers|last=Gardner|first=Lyn|date=8 August 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> This piece centres around the story of her then fianc\u00e9, Tim Grayburn, and his battle with mental health, more specifically depression.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/fake-it-til-you-make-it-bryony-kimmings-has-made-a-drama-out-of-her-boyfriends-depression-10395322.html|title=Fake It 'Til You Make It: Bryony Kimmings has made a drama out of her|date=2015-07-19|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Through song, dance, slapstick, voice-over, masks, the performance gives the audience an insight into depression, mainly through the male perspective and why they are more likely to hide it from friends, family and colleagues as this is a common occurrence in society that isn't talked about as much.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2015/fake-til-make/|title=Fake It \u2019Til You Make It {{!}} Review {{!}} Theatre|last=Awde|first=Nick|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n* ''That Catherine Bennett Show'' (2014). Premiered at the [[Southbank Centre]], London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exeuntmagazine.com/reviews/that-catherine-bennett-show/|title=That Catherine Bennett Show - Exeunt Magazine|website=exeuntmagazine.com|first=Stewart|last=Pringle|date=18 February 2014|access-date=9 February 2017}}</ref> This performance was created by Kimmings and her nine year old niece, looking at creating the pop star culture to create their own dinosaur-loving, bike-riding, tuna pasta-eating, alternative pop star called Catherine Bennett. It is seen as being a show about This is a show about family activism, children\u2019s rights and believing in your own power as an individual to change the world, even as a child.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/thatcbshow.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> This performance was specifically for children aged 6-9 years old. The use of the Horrible Histories Suffragettes song allows the performance to be educational but also recognisable to the audience, as most children have watched Horrible Histories either at home or in school. This performance can be looked as inspiration for children to change the world.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Costa|first=Maddy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/feb/18/play-time-bryony-kimmings-catherine-bennett|title=Play time: That Catherine Bennett Show \u2013 review|date=2014-02-18|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n* ''Credible Likeable Superstar Role Model'' (2013). Premiered at the Pleasance Dome, Edinburgh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/edinburgh-2013-credible-likeable-superstar-rolemodel-a-bold-brilliant-show-from-bryony-kimmings-8776459.html|title=Edinburgh 2013: Credible Likeable Superstar Rolemodel - A bold,|date=20 August 2013|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> This show explores Kimmings personal relationship with sex and alcohol. Alongside her on stage is her nine-year old niece to push Kimmings to create her alter-ego Catherine Bennett,  an alternative pop star who is an expert on dinosaurs, and who also loves tuna, pasta and animals. The piece was created to highlight the hyper-sexualisation of tweenage girls, where there role models are the likes of Katy Perry and Rihanna. This piece isn't described as a theatre but more as a call to arms against those who profit from selling thongs to children. The piece can be described as being cool, funny, heart-warming and infectiously optimistic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gardner|first=Lyn|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/aug/19/credible-likeable-superstar-role-model-edinburgh-review|title=Credible Likeable Superstar Role Model \u2013 Edinburgh festival 2013 review|date=2013-08-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n*''Heartache.Heartbreak.'' (2012). Premiered at Culturgest, Lisbon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/heartache.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=9 February 2017}}</ref> This performance is about an investigative journalist who is conducting door to door enquiries about how to get over a broken heart, the responses she gets are a mixture of the trite, nihilistic and the devastatingly sad and each of them being replayed with hilarious performative embodiment or mockery. What emerges from this performance is how universal all the voices are, making the performance fluid, expansive and physical. This performance is a stack of individual coping mechanisms harvested and smashed together into one big malfunctioning machinery of misery, making the piece relatable to the audience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exeuntmagazine.com/reviews/heartache-heartbreak/|title=Heartache. Heartbreak.|website=Exeunt Magazine|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*''Kablooey!'' (2012). Premiered at [[Battersea Arts Centre]], London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/9626254/The-Good-Neighbour-Battersea-Arts-Centre-review.html|title=The Good Neighbour, Battersea Arts Centre, review|newspaper=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en}}</ref> This performance is a ten minute piece that was made for people at a time, both adults and children. The idea is to help Barbra Bliss, whose flat has been singed and is the former life and soul of the party, escape the ''Kablooey'', which is an esploding spell that has been put on her home by a power-hungry housing officer. The aim of the performance is for the audience to solve the riddle, whilst also aiming to make Barbra laugh again, in hopes of stopping the room exploding again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/kablooey.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*''Mummy Time'' (2011). Premiered at The Junction, Cambridge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exeuntmagazine.com/features/sampled/|title=Sampled - Exeunt Magazine|website=exeuntmagazine.com|access-date=9 February 2017}}</ref> This is a ten minute piece that has been described as a high octane, funny and ultimately moving 1-to-1 experience for festivals. An audience member becomes the fourth member of the family, who has just got home from school. The mum is knee deep in sheets, nan is in the hospital and the uncle is on the phone for a score. This performance follows the audience member eating 'poverty tea', doing their homework and helping wrap and weigh drugs for mum, until child services interrupt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/mummytime.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n*''A Date with the Night'' (2011). Premiered at ANTI-Contemporary Art Festival, Kuopio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/a-date-with-the-night.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=9 February 2017}}</ref> This performance was a one-off, 1-to-1 piece that compressed a messy and hideous drunk blind date to one length of a mega-mix song. It starts with an innocent dinner, through to bars, clubs, alleys and then ultimately straight into bed. Kimmings and her single audience member created the date together, improvising small talk, lots of shots and disco dancing, so that when morning dawned, the regret and shame set in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/a-date-with-the-night.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*''7 Day Drunk'' (2011).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/comedy/bryony-kimmings-southbank-centre-review-8499163.html|title=Bryony Kimmings, Southbank Centre - review|date=18 March 2013|newspaper=Evening Standard|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*''Sex Idiot'' (2010)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2010/aug/22/sex-idiot-edinburgh-review|title=Sex Idiot {{!}} Edinburgh theatre review|last=Gardner|first=Lyn|date=2010-08-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-17|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*The Hall of Gratuitous Praise (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*Mega (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*The Fanny Song (2010) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*Double Dare (2010)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*A Pacifist's Guide to the War on Cancer (2016) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n=== As playwright ===\n*''A Pacifist's Guide to the War on Cancer'' (2016). Book by Bryony Kimmings and [[Brian Lobel]]. Lyrics by Bryony Kimmings. Co-Produced by Approach Complicite Associates and National Theatre.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/oct/20/a-pacifists-guide-to-the-war-on-cancer-review-national-theatre|title=A Pacifist's Guide to the War on Cancer review \u2013 bold musical demystifies the disease|last=Billington|first=Michael|date=20 October 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n*The Boys Project (2017).  A performance created by Bryony Kimmings which engaged young men from council estates all over the UK, including Leeds, Cardiff, Peterborough, Birmingham, Manchester and London. It was a long term art and activism project which exploded media stereotypes and the political marginalisation of the young. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalcourttheatre.com/boys-project-undergrowth/|title=The Boys' Project: The Undergrowth|date=2017-05-05|website=Royal Court|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n=== As screenwriter ===\n*''[[Last Christmas (film)|Last Christmas]]'' (2019). Co-screenwriter with [[Emma Thompson]]. A romantic comedy film directed by [[Paul Feig]], inspired by the [[Wham!]] song \"[[Last Christmas]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pulver |first1=Andrew |title=George Michael-inspired 'holiday romance' film Last Christmas in the works |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/19/george-michael-last-christmas |accessdate=14 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=19 July 2018}}</ref> \n\n== Approach ==\nKnown primarily for creating autobiographical work, Kimmings achieved notoriety with her 2010 piece ''Sex Idiot''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/sexidiot.html|title=Sex Idiot|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> In it, she revealed her sexual and her romantic history after discovering she had contracted an STI and told of the quest to find out which of her former partners had given it on to her.<ref name=\"TM\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/theatre/interview-bryony-kimmings-sex-idiot|title=Interview: Bryony Kimmings, Sex idiot - Theatre|website=Time Out London|language=en|date=2011-03-18|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> She toured this show until 2015. In her 2011 piece ''7 Day Drunk'' Kimmings collaborated with a team of scientists to analyse the impact of alcohol on her creativity.<ref name=\"7Day\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/7daydrunk.html|title=7 Day Drunk|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview in March 2011, speaking of the drivers behind her work Kimmings said: \"I guess in a way it is an artist's duty to say and explore the things that are untouchable, or hard to talk about.\"<ref name=\"RR\" />\n\nIn a 2012 interview for Pulse Fringe Festival, Kimmings introduces herself as \"an artist who makes autobiographical work\" she continues to say her work \"always follows a kind of autobiographical experiment that I go on.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4_VLGmM-iLk | title=An Interview With Bryony Kimmings | publisher=Pulse Fringe Festival/youtube | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> Her profile on the British Council of Drama and Dance website says: \"Bryony works autobiographically and begins the development of her work with a social experiment. She is inspired by the taboos and anomalies of British culture and her work promotes the airing of her own dirty laundry to oil conversations on seemingly difficult subjects.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dramaanddance.britishcouncil.org/artists-and-companies/profiles/bryony-kimmings/ | title=Bryony Kimmings | publisher=British Council | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKimmings was born in [[Huntingdon]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2016/bryony-kimmings-i-didnt-know-anything-about-musicals-but-i-love-fannying-about/|title=Bryony Kimmings: \u2018I didn\u2019t know anything about musicals but I love fannying about\u2019 {{!}} Interviews|last=Shenton|first=Mark|date=2016-10-20|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> and grew up in [[St Ives, Cambridgeshire]].<ref name=beyond>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beyondthejoke.co.uk/content/1954/interview-bryony-kimmings|title=Interview: Bryony Kimmings|date=2015-08-06|website=Beyond The Joke|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> She has an older sister, whose then 9-year-old daughter inspired her to develop her 2013 show ''Credible Likeable Superstar Role Model''.<ref name=beyond/>\n\nIn November 2015, Kimmings gave birth to her son Frank. The boy's father is her fianc\u00e9 at the time, Tim Grayburn. Frank was diagnosed with [[West Syndrome]], a form of [[epilepsy]], soon after he was born.<ref name=\"go\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/bryony-kimmings-interview-im-narcissistic-i-am-the-art-a3928036.html|title=Bryony Kimmings on rising from the ashes and having no taboos|date=2018-09-05|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> In her 2018 show ''I'm a Phoenix, Bitch'', Kimmings processed how she experienced post-natal depression, had a severely ill infant and went through a break-up all in one year.<ref name=\"go\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebryonykimmings.tumblr.com/?og=1|title=Bryony Kimmings|website=thebryonykimmings.tumblr.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n===''Sex Idiot''===\n* Total Theatre Award 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exeuntmagazine.com/features/bryony-kimmings/2/|title=Bryony Kimmings|publisher=exeunt|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> \n* Listed in Time Out magazine's Best of the Year (2010) \u2013 off-West End and Fringe Theatre category<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/gallery/733/best-of-the-year-2010-off-west-end-and-fringe-theatre/7|title=Best of the year 2010: off-West End and fringe theatre|work=Time Out Magazine|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> \n* West Australian Arts Editor Award 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outinperth.com/fringe-world-concludes-awards-ceremony/|title=Fringe World Concludes with Awards Ceremony|date=2015-02-23|website=OUTInPerth - LGBTIQ News and Culture|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> \n* [[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] Best Comedy Award, [[Adelaide Fringe Festival]] 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/entertainment/adelaide-fringe/adelaide-festival-2015-adelaide-fringe-2015-the-best-the-rest-and-the-most-distressed/news-story/338edfb1335fc28011dcf45f000dbb62|title=The best, the rest and the most distressed|date=2015-03-13|website=www.adelaidenow.com.au|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> \n\n===''Fake it \u2018til you Make it''===\n* Best Theatre Award, [[Fringe World|Fringe World Perth]] 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fringefund.org/award-winners|title=Award Winners|website=Fringe Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n* Best Theatre Award, Adelaide Fringe Festival 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artsreview.com.au/2015-adelaide-fringe-wraps-up-as-festival-awards-announced/|title=2015 Adelaide Fringe wraps up as Festival Awards announced|date=2015-03-16|website=Australian Arts Review|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n* Herald Angel Award, Edinburgh Fringe Festivatl 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/edinburgh-theatre/news/edinburgh-festival-fringe-awards-2015_38628.html|title=Edinburgh awards 2015 - Who won what? {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n* Short-listed for the Amnesty Freedom of Expression Award, Edinburgh Fringe Festival 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/press-releases/amnesty-freedom-expression-award-2015-shortlist-announced|title=Amnesty Freedom of Expression Award 2015 Shortlist Announced|website=www.amnesty.org.uk|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bryonykimmings.com/ Bryony Kimmings' website]\n* [http://thebryonykimmings.tumblr.com/ Bryony Kimmings' blog]\n* [http://7daydrunk.tumblr.com/ 7 Day Drunk blog]\n* {{imdb name|6507883}}\n* {{Twitter|bryonykimmings}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kimmings, Bryony}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English performance artists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Bryony Kimmings''' (born 30 March 1981){{cn|date=July 2018}} is a British live artist based in [[London]] and [[Cambridgeshire]]. She is an associate artist of the [[Soho Theatre]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.sohotheatre.com/writers/writers/bryony-kimmings/ | title=Bryony Kimmings | publisher=Soho Theatre Company Ltd | accessdate=18 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160618200319/http://www.sohotheatre.com/writers/writers/bryony-kimmings/|archivedate=18 June 2016}}</ref> and, in 2016, was commissioned to write ''The Pacifist's Guide to the War on Cancer'' for [[Complicite]] Associates.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.complicite.org/productions/APacifistsGuideToTheWarOnCancer | title=A Pacifist's Guide to the War on Cancer | publisher=Complicite | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe creates multi-platform art works to provoke change.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://theweekendedition.com.au/the-locals/bryony-kimmings/ | title=Bryony Kimmings, performance artist, Fake It \u2019Til You Make It |first= Chrisanthi |last=Demos|work=The Weekend Edition |date=18 June 2015 | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> Her work centres mostly around \"social experiments\",<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/magazine/archive/2014/06/play/bryony-kimmings |title=Bryony Kimmings explores link between drinking with creativity |first=Madhumita |last=Venkataramanan |magazine=Wired |department=Neuroscience |date=June 2014 |accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> which in the past have included the artist retracing an [[Sexually transmitted infection|STI]] to its source,<ref name=TM>{{cite web | url=http://themusic.com.au/interviews/all/2014/03/26/bryony-kimmings/24747/ | title=Arts Interview Bryony Kimmings | publisher=Street Press Australia Pty Ltd |date= 26 March 2014|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> spending seven days in a controlled environment in a constant state of intoxication<ref name=7Day>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/aug/19/7-day-drunk-review | title=7 Day Drunk \u2013 review |first=Lyn|last= Gardner| newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=Guardian News and Media Limited |date=20 August 2011| accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> and becoming a pop star invented by a nine-year-old.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/aug/06/female-role-models-bryony-kimmings | title=Lack of female role models? Make one up: Bryony Kimmings' homemade hero |first=Catherine|last=Love| newspaper=The Guardian |date= 7 August 2013| accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs well as appearing at the Soho Theatre, Kimmings' work has toured across the world including: [[Antifest]] (Finland), Culturgest (Portugal), Fusebox Festival (Texas), [[Southbank Centre|The Southbank Centre]], [[Melbourne International Comedy Festival]] (Australia), and Lisinski Operahouse (Croatia).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/about.html | title=Bryony Kimmings | publisher=Bryony Kimmings | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nKimmings graduated with a degree in Modern Drama from [[Brunel University]] in 2003.<ref name=\"BKInt\">{{cite web | url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/comedy/bryony-kimmings-interview-joke-therapy-10426133.html | title=Bryony Kimmings interview: Joke therapy | newspaper=Evening Standard |first=Bruce|last=Dessau|date= 30 July 2015|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> In a 2011 interview she said of her time at Brunel: \"It was Live Art and the history of performance artists that excited me the most\", and so immediately afterwards she established the company 'Glass Eyed' with friends. 'Glass Eyed' created work for two years before being dissolved.<ref name=\"RR\">{{cite web | url=http://www.run-riot.com/articles/blogs/interview-bryony-kimmings-talks-sex-booze-and-performance | title=Interview: Bryony Kimmings Talks Sex, Booze and Performance | publisher=RunRiot.com | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 she began ''Celebrityville'' a soap cabaret following the lives of forgotten celebrities living in a fictional town. A new episode was created every month between 2006 and 2008. Describing working on ''Celebrityville'' Kimmings said \"this gave me a baptism of fire really, making such a large volume of work, learning about how to run a night, what to do if things broke half way through, making costumes, doing marketing - everything.\"<ref name=RR/> When ''Celebrityville'' ended, Kimmings began to explore a solo live art career with autobiographical themes.<ref name=RR/>\n\n==Shows==\n\n=== Performance work ===\n* ''I'm a Phoenix, Bitch'' (2018). Premiered at the [[Battersea Arts Centre]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/bryony-kimmings-im-a-phoenix-bitch-battersea_48085.html|title=Bryony Kimmings' I'm a Phoenix, Bitch to return to Battersea Arts Centre in 2019 {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> This piece can be viewed as a subversive feminist musical piece, with elements of a pop-video, horror film, art installation and therapy session. This piece comes from a deeply personal place for Kimmings, taking inspiration from a moment in 2015 when she broke up with her boyfriend, lost her mind and nearly lost her baby.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/oct/09/im-a-phoenix-bitch-review-bryony-kimmings|title=I\u2019m a Phoenix, Bitch review \u2013 wacky, warped and wonderful|last=Gillinson|first=Miriam|date=2018-10-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2016, Kimmings nearly drowning, followed by post-natal breakdowns, an imploding relationship and an extremely sick child that left her feeling overwhelmed with life. Four years later, she is able to deal with her life again, but she is wearing the scars of that year like having a weight on her shoulders. It provokes the questions of: Who do we become after trauma? How do we turn pain into power? How do we fly instead of drown?<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://homemcr.org/production/im-a-phoenix-bitch/|title=I'm a Phoenix, Bitch|website=HOME|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*''Fake it \u2018til you Make it'' (2015). Premiered at the [[Traverse Theatre]], Edinburgh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2015/aug/08/fake-it-til-you-make-it-edinburgh-festival-review-traverse-bryony-kimmings-tim-grayburn-depression|title=Fake It 'Til You Make It at Edinburgh festival review \u2013 divides audience into smilers and sobbers|last=Gardner|first=Lyn|date=8 August 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> This piece centres around the story of her then fianc\u00e9, Tim Grayburn, and his battle with mental health, more specifically depression.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/features/fake-it-til-you-make-it-bryony-kimmings-has-made-a-drama-out-of-her-boyfriends-depression-10395322.html|title=Fake It 'Til You Make It: Bryony Kimmings has made a drama out of her|date=2015-07-19|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> Through song, dance, slapstick, voice-over, masks, the performance gives the audience an insight into depression, mainly through the male perspective and why they are more likely to hide it from friends, family and colleagues as this is a common occurrence in society that isn't talked about as much.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2015/fake-til-make/|title=Fake It \u2019Til You Make It {{!}} Review {{!}} Theatre|last=Awde|first=Nick|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n* ''That Catherine Bennett Show'' (2014). Premiered at the [[Southbank Centre]], London.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exeuntmagazine.com/reviews/that-catherine-bennett-show/|title=That Catherine Bennett Show - Exeunt Magazine|website=exeuntmagazine.com|first=Stewart|last=Pringle|date=18 February 2014|access-date=9 February 2017}}</ref> This performance was created by Kimmings and her nine year old niece, looking at creating the pop star culture to create their own dinosaur-loving, bike-riding, tuna pasta-eating, alternative pop star called Catherine Bennett. It is seen as being a show about This is a show about family activism, children\u2019s rights and believing in your own power as an individual to change the world, even as a child.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/thatcbshow.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> This performance was specifically for children aged 6-9 years old. The use of the Horrible Histories Suffragettes song allows the performance to be educational but also recognisable to the audience, as most children have watched Horrible Histories either at home or in school. This performance can be looked as inspiration for children to change the world.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Costa|first=Maddy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2014/feb/18/play-time-bryony-kimmings-catherine-bennett|title=Play time: That Catherine Bennett Show \u2013 review|date=2014-02-18|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-27|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n* ''Credible Likeable Superstar Role Model'' (2013). Premiered at the Pleasance Dome, Edinburgh.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/edinburgh-2013-credible-likeable-superstar-rolemodel-a-bold-brilliant-show-from-bryony-kimmings-8776459.html|title=Edinburgh 2013: Credible Likeable Superstar Rolemodel - A bold,|date=20 August 2013|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref> This show explores Kimmings personal relationship with sex and alcohol. Alongside her on stage is her nine-year old niece to push Kimmings to create her alter-ego Catherine Bennett,  an alternative pop star who is an expert on dinosaurs, and who also loves tuna, pasta and animals. The piece was created to highlight the hyper-sexualisation of tweenage girls, where there role models are the likes of Katy Perry and Rihanna. This piece isn't described as a theatre but more as a call to arms against those who profit from selling thongs to children. The piece can be described as being cool, funny, heart-warming and infectiously optimistic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gardner|first=Lyn|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/aug/19/credible-likeable-superstar-role-model-edinburgh-review|title=Credible Likeable Superstar Role Model \u2013 Edinburgh festival 2013 review|date=2013-08-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n*''Heartache.Heartbreak.'' (2012). Premiered at Culturgest, Lisbon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/heartache.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=9 February 2017}}</ref> This performance is about an investigative journalist who is conducting door to door enquiries about how to get over a broken heart, the responses she gets are a mixture of the trite, nihilistic and the devastatingly sad and each of them being replayed with hilarious performative embodiment or mockery. What emerges from this performance is how universal all the voices are, making the performance fluid, expansive and physical. This performance is a stack of individual coping mechanisms harvested and smashed together into one big malfunctioning machinery of misery, making the piece relatable to the audience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exeuntmagazine.com/reviews/heartache-heartbreak/|title=Heartache. Heartbreak.|website=Exeunt Magazine|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*''Kablooey!'' (2012). Premiered at [[Battersea Arts Centre]], London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/9626254/The-Good-Neighbour-Battersea-Arts-Centre-review.html|title=The Good Neighbour, Battersea Arts Centre, review|newspaper=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en}}</ref> This performance is a ten minute piece that was made for people at a time, both adults and children. The idea is to help Barbra Bliss, whose flat has been singed and is the former life and soul of the party, escape the ''Kablooey'', which is an esploding spell that has been put on her home by a power-hungry housing officer. The aim of the performance is for the audience to solve the riddle, whilst also aiming to make Barbra laugh again, in hopes of stopping the room exploding again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/kablooey.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*''Mummy Time'' (2011). Premiered at The Junction, Cambridge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://exeuntmagazine.com/features/sampled/|title=Sampled - Exeunt Magazine|website=exeuntmagazine.com|access-date=9 February 2017}}</ref> This is a ten minute piece that has been described as a high octane, funny and ultimately moving 1-to-1 experience for festivals. An audience member becomes the fourth member of the family, who has just got home from school. The mum is knee deep in sheets, nan is in the hospital and the uncle is on the phone for a score. This performance follows the audience member eating 'poverty tea', doing their homework and helping wrap and weigh drugs for mum, until child services interrupt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/mummytime.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> \n*''A Date with the Night'' (2011). Premiered at ANTI-Contemporary Art Festival, Kuopio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/a-date-with-the-night.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=9 February 2017}}</ref> This performance was a one-off, 1-to-1 piece that compressed a messy and hideous drunk blind date to one length of a mega-mix song. It starts with an innocent dinner, through to bars, clubs, alleys and then ultimately straight into bed. Kimmings and her single audience member created the date together, improvising small talk, lots of shots and disco dancing, so that when morning dawned, the regret and shame set in.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/a-date-with-the-night.html|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*''7 Day Drunk'' (2011).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/comedy/bryony-kimmings-southbank-centre-review-8499163.html|title=Bryony Kimmings, Southbank Centre - review|date=18 March 2013|newspaper=Evening Standard|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n*''Sex Idiot'' (2010)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2010/aug/22/sex-idiot-edinburgh-review|title=Sex Idiot {{!}} Edinburgh theatre review|last=Gardner|first=Lyn|date=2010-08-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-17|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*The Hall of Gratuitous Praise (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*Mega (2011)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*The Fanny Song (2010) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*Double Dare (2010)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*A Pacifist's Guide to the War on Cancer (2016) <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/|title=Bryony Kimmings Ltd.|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n=== As playwright ===\n*''A Pacifist's Guide to the War on Cancer'' (2016). Book by Bryony Kimmings and [[Brian Lobel]]. Lyrics by Bryony Kimmings. Co-Produced by Approach Complicite Associates and National Theatre.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/oct/20/a-pacifists-guide-to-the-war-on-cancer-review-national-theatre|title=A Pacifist's Guide to the War on Cancer review \u2013 bold musical demystifies the disease|last=Billington|first=Michael|date=20 October 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=9 February 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> \n*The Boys Project (2017).  A performance created by Bryony Kimmings which engaged young men from council estates all over the UK, including Leeds, Cardiff, Peterborough, Birmingham, Manchester and London. It was a long term art and activism project which exploded media stereotypes and the political marginalisation of the young. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalcourttheatre.com/boys-project-undergrowth/|title=The Boys' Project: The Undergrowth|date=2017-05-05|website=Royal Court|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n=== As screenwriter ===\n*''[[Last Christmas (film)|Last Christmas]]'' (2019). Co-screenwriter with [[Emma Thompson]]. A romantic comedy film directed by [[Paul Feig]], inspired by the [[Wham!]] song \"[[Last Christmas]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pulver |first1=Andrew |title=George Michael-inspired 'holiday romance' film Last Christmas in the works |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jul/19/george-michael-last-christmas |accessdate=14 August 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=19 July 2018}}</ref> \n\n== Approach ==\nKnown primarily for creating autobiographical work, Kimmings achieved notoriety with her 2010 piece ''Sex Idiot''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/sexidiot.html|title=Sex Idiot|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> In it, she revealed her sexual and her romantic history after discovering she had contracted an STI and told of the quest to find out which of her former partners had given it on to her.<ref name=\"TM\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/theatre/interview-bryony-kimmings-sex-idiot|title=Interview: Bryony Kimmings, Sex idiot - Theatre|website=Time Out London|language=en|date=2011-03-18|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> She toured this show until 2015. In her 2011 piece ''7 Day Drunk'' Kimmings collaborated with a team of scientists to analyse the impact of alcohol on her creativity.<ref name=\"7Day\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bryonykimmings.com/7daydrunk.html|title=7 Day Drunk|website=www.bryonykimmings.com|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview in March 2011, speaking of the drivers behind her work Kimmings said: \"I guess in a way it is an artist's duty to say and explore the things that are untouchable, or hard to talk about.\"<ref name=\"RR\" />\n\nIn a 2012 interview for Pulse Fringe Festival, Kimmings introduces herself as \"an artist who makes autobiographical work\" she continues to say her work \"always follows a kind of autobiographical experiment that I go on.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4_VLGmM-iLk | title=An Interview With Bryony Kimmings | publisher=Pulse Fringe Festival/youtube | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> Her profile on the British Council of Drama and Dance website says: \"Bryony works autobiographically and begins the development of her work with a social experiment. She is inspired by the taboos and anomalies of British culture and her work promotes the airing of her own dirty laundry to oil conversations on seemingly difficult subjects.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://dramaanddance.britishcouncil.org/artists-and-companies/profiles/bryony-kimmings/ | title=Bryony Kimmings | publisher=British Council | accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKimmings was born in [[Huntingdon]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2016/bryony-kimmings-i-didnt-know-anything-about-musicals-but-i-love-fannying-about/|title=Bryony Kimmings: \u2018I didn\u2019t know anything about musicals but I love fannying about\u2019 {{!}} Interviews|last=Shenton|first=Mark|date=2016-10-20|website=The Stage|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> and grew up in [[St Ives, Cambridgeshire]].<ref name=beyond>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beyondthejoke.co.uk/content/1954/interview-bryony-kimmings|title=Interview: Bryony Kimmings|date=2015-08-06|website=Beyond The Joke|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> She has an older sister, whose then 9-year-old daughter inspired her to develop her 2013 show ''Credible Likeable Superstar Role Model''.<ref name=beyond/>\n\nIn November 2015, Kimmings gave birth to her son Frank. The boy's father is her fianc\u00e9 at the time, Tim Grayburn. Frank was diagnosed with [[West Syndrome]], a form of [[epilepsy]], soon after he was born.<ref name=\"go\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/theatre/bryony-kimmings-interview-im-narcissistic-i-am-the-art-a3928036.html|title=Bryony Kimmings on rising from the ashes and having no taboos|date=2018-09-05|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> In her 2018 show ''I'm a Phoenix, Bitch'', Kimmings processed how she experienced post-natal depression, had a severely ill infant and went through a break-up all in one year.<ref name=\"go\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thebryonykimmings.tumblr.com/?og=1|title=Bryony Kimmings|website=thebryonykimmings.tumblr.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n===''Sex Idiot''===\n* Total Theatre Award 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://exeuntmagazine.com/features/bryony-kimmings/2/|title=Bryony Kimmings|publisher=exeunt|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> \n* Listed in Time Out magazine's Best of the Year (2010) \u2013 off-West End and Fringe Theatre category<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/london/gallery/733/best-of-the-year-2010-off-west-end-and-fringe-theatre/7|title=Best of the year 2010: off-West End and fringe theatre|work=Time Out Magazine|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref> \n* West Australian Arts Editor Award 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outinperth.com/fringe-world-concludes-awards-ceremony/|title=Fringe World Concludes with Awards Ceremony|date=2015-02-23|website=OUTInPerth - LGBTIQ News and Culture|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> \n* [[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The Advertiser]] Best Comedy Award, [[Adelaide Fringe Festival]] 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adelaidenow.com.au/entertainment/adelaide-fringe/adelaide-festival-2015-adelaide-fringe-2015-the-best-the-rest-and-the-most-distressed/news-story/338edfb1335fc28011dcf45f000dbb62|title=The best, the rest and the most distressed|date=2015-03-13|website=www.adelaidenow.com.au|language=en|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref> \n\n===''Fake it \u2018til you Make it''===\n* Best Theatre Award, [[Fringe World|Fringe World Perth]] 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fringefund.org/award-winners|title=Award Winners|website=Fringe Fund|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n* Best Theatre Award, Adelaide Fringe Festival 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://artsreview.com.au/2015-adelaide-fringe-wraps-up-as-festival-awards-announced/|title=2015 Adelaide Fringe wraps up as Festival Awards announced|date=2015-03-16|website=Australian Arts Review|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n* Herald Angel Award, Edinburgh Fringe Festivatl 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whatsonstage.com/edinburgh-theatre/news/edinburgh-festival-fringe-awards-2015_38628.html|title=Edinburgh awards 2015 - Who won what? {{!}} WhatsOnStage|website=www.whatsonstage.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n* Short-listed for the Amnesty Freedom of Expression Award, Edinburgh Fringe Festival 2015<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org.uk/press-releases/amnesty-freedom-expression-award-2015-shortlist-announced|title=Amnesty Freedom of Expression Award 2015 Shortlist Announced|website=www.amnesty.org.uk|access-date=2019-08-17}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bryonykimmings.com/ Bryony Kimmings' website]\n* [http://thebryonykimmings.tumblr.com/ Bryony Kimmings' blog]\n* [http://7daydrunk.tumblr.com/ 7 Day Drunk blog]\n* {{imdb name|6507883}}\n* {{Twitter|bryonykimmings}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kimmings, Bryony}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English performance artists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Alishausernametaken", "label": "safe", "comment": "citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bryony_Kimmings"}
{"title_page": "Maheshwar", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Maheshwar\n| other_name              = Mheysur <ref>https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~292725~90063968:India-VI?sort=Pub_List_No_InitialSort%2CPub_Date%2CPub_List_No%2CSeries_No&qvq=q:Malwa;sort:Pub_List_No_InitialSort%2CPub_Date%2CPub_List_No%2CSeries_No;lc:RUMSEY~8~1&mi=0&trs=3</ref>\n| settlement_type         = Town\n| image_skyline           = Maheshwar 02.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = A street in Maheshwar\n| pushpin_map             = India Madhya Pradesh\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|22.11|N|75.35|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = Khargone\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 =\n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 154\n| population_total        = 30000\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 451224\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 07283\n| registration_plate      = MP-10\n| website                 = {{URL|www.khargone.nic.in}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Maheshwar''' is a town in [[Khargone]] district of [[Madhya Pradesh]] state, in central [[India]]. It is located 13&nbsp;km east of National Highway 3 (Agra-Mumbai highway) and 91&nbsp;km from [[Indore]], the commercial capital of the state. The Town lies on the north bank of the [[Narmada River]].\nIt was the capital of the [[Malwa]] during the [[Maratha]] [[Holkar|Holkar reign]] till 6 January 1818, when the capital was shifted to [[Indore]] by Malhar Rao Holkar III.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word Maheshwar in Hindi means ''Great God, ''an epithet of [[Lord Shiva]].\n\n==History and mythology==\nWriters such as [[Hasmukh Dhirajlal Sankalia|HD Sankalia]],<ref>{{cite book |author=Hasmukhlal Dhirajlal Sankalia |title=Aspects of Indian History and Archaeology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2pwtAAAAMAAJ |year=1977 |publisher=B. R. |page=218 }}</ref> [[Pramatha Nath Bose|PN Bose]]<ref name=\"PNBose_1882\">{{cite book |author=PN Bose |publisher=Asiatic Society |location=Calcutta, India |title=Note on Mahishmati |work=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VVsyAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA129 |year=1882 |pages=129}}</ref> and [[Francis Wilford]],<ref name=\"PNBose_1882\"/> among others, identify Maheshwar as the ancient town of [[Mahishmati]].\n\nMaheshwar is believed to be built on the site of the ancient city of Somvanshya Shastrarjun Kshatriya, and was the capital of king [[Kartavirya Arjuna]], (Shree Shastrarjun) who is mentioned in the [[Sanskrit]] epics [[Ramayana]] and [[Mahabharata]]. According to a popular legend, one day the King Sahasrarjun and his 500 wives went to the river for a picnic. When the wives wanted a vast play area, the King stopped the mighty river Narmada with his 1000 arms. While they were all enjoying themselves, [[Ravana]] flew by in his Pushpak Vimana. Downstream, when he saw the dry river bed, he thought it was an ideal place to pray to Lord Shiva. He made a Shivalinga out of the sand and began to pray. When Sahasrajuna's wives were done playing and they stepped out of the river bed, he let the waters flow. The voluminous river flowed down sweeping Ravana's Shivalinga along, messing up his prayers. Furious, Ravana tracked Sahasrajuna and challenged him. Armed to the hilt the mighty Ravana was in for a huge surprise. The mighty Sahasrarjuna with the 1000 arms pinned Ravana to the ground. Then he placed 10 lamps on his heads and one on his hand. After tying up Ravana, Sahasrarjuna dragged him home and tied him up to the cradle pole of his son. A humiliated Ravana stayed prisoner until his release was secured. [[Jamadagni]] rishi, [[Renuka]] Devi and Lord [[Parashurama]] with whom Kartavirya Arjuna's story is closely associated also lived nearby.\n\nIn Mahabharata,<ref>[http://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m02/m02030.htm story of Mahishmati in Mahabharata]</ref> there is a narration of an unusual tradition wherein marriage as a civil institution was not universal in Mahishmati unlike in rest of Aryavarta, which is also narrated in the Telugu-language ''[[Andhra Mahabharatam|Andhra Mahabharata]]'' in \u2018Sabha parva\u2019.\n\nAs per the legend, there was a Nishada king named Nila who ruled over Mahishmati. King Nila had a daughter who was exceedingly beautiful. So much so that [[Agni]] (lord of fire) fell in love with her which was reciprocated. The princess always used to stay near the sacred fire of her father, causing it to blaze up with vigour. And king Nila's sacred fire, even if fanned, would not blaze until agitated by the gentle breath of her lips. Agni, assuming the form of a [[Brahman (cattle)|Brahman]] starts courting with the princess for long. But, one day the couple was discovered by the king, who became furious. Nila thereupon ordered the Brahman to be punished according to law. At this the illustrious deity flamed up in wrath and beholding the terrible flame, the king felt terrified and bent his head low on the ground. King hails Lord Agni and says he cannot punish a god who is responsible for the origin of Vedas, source of all Knowledge and Dharma. Pacified Agni then grants a boon to Nishada, and the King requests for the protection of his kingdom from any invasions. Agni swears to protect his kingdom on the condition that the king should sanctify pleasure out of pure love a legitimate action in his kingdom. Liberated from the orthodoxy of marriage as a prelude, women of Mahishmati enjoyed freedom that was then unheard of elsewhere in Arya-Varta.\n\nYears later, after the epic war the victorious [[Yudhishthira]] plans on conducting a [[Yagna]] by winning over everyone else on Earth. [[Sahadeva]], the youngest of Pandavas knowing that Lord Agni was protecting the Nishada kingdom, prays to Lord Agni successfully and there upon moves to [[Saurashtra people|Saurashtra]] kingdom.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Andhra Mahabharatha|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{page needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nOf note, even to this day, the Sahasrarjun temple at Maheshwar lights 11 lamps in honour of Lord Agni blessing the Kingdom. Alternatively, this tradition is attributed to Sahasrarjun queens humiliating captive ten-headed Ravana by lighting up candles on his foreheads.\n\nIn the late eighteenth century, Maheshwar served as the capital of the great [[Maratha]] queen [[Rajmata Ahilya Devi Holkar]]. She embellished the city with many buildings and public works, and it is home to her palace, as well as numerous temples, a [[fort]], and riverfront ''ghats'' (broad stone steps which step down to the river).\n\nJagadguru Kripaluji Maharaj has performed various akhand (continues) sankirtan outside the Shiva temple at Maheshwar for more than months. Even though Kripaluji was from mahu (30&nbsp;km from Maheshwar), he frequently visited this place in his early life with devotees of lord Krishna to perform sankirtan on the banks of the Narmada river in Maheshwar.\n\n[[File:Maheshwar Fort - Exterior 03.jpg|thumb|left|Fort Ahilya of the [[Holkar]] dynasty, in Maheshwar.]]\n[[File:Maheshwar fort.JPG|thumb|right|Ahilya Fort at Maheshwar.]]\n[[File:Narmada river, Maheshwari.jpg|thumb|Narmada river, Maheshwari]]\n[[File:Fort of maheshwar.jpg|thumb|Fort of Maheshwar and Narmada river]]\n\n==Demographics==\n{{As of|2001}} India [[census]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Maheshwar had a population of 24000. Males constitute 51% of the population and females 49%. Maheshwar has an average literacy rate of 67%, higher than the national average of 59.5%: male literacy is 75%, and female literacy is 59%. In Maheshwar, 14% of the population is under 6&nbsp;years of age.\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Religion in Maheshwar \n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|77.86}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|20.70}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism|Jains]]|pink|0.91}}\n{{bar percent|[[Sikh]]s |red|0.35}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|0.2}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|blue|0.11}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions<br />\n\u2020<small>Includes [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] (0.2%).</small>\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:PC080025.JPG|right|180px|thumb|Maheshwari sari laced with bright ''[[Zari]]'' ([[brocade]])]]\n[[File:Looms at Rehwa society, Maheshwari handloom sarees weavers society, Maheshwar.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Looms at Rehwa society, Maheshwari handloom sarees weavers society, Maheshwar.]]Maheshwar has been a centre of handloom [[weaving]] since the 5th century. Maheshwar is the home of one of India's finest handloom fabric traditions. It is noted as a centre for weaving colourful Maheshwari sarees.<ref>[http://www.qohindia.com/collections/all/maheshwari Maheshwari Sarees]</ref> It rose to popularity under the rule of strong maratha leader Queen [[Ahilyabai Holkar|Devi Ahilya Bai Holkar]]. Ahilya Bai wanted royal gifts for the royal guest. Hence weavers from Mandu and Surat were hired and Maheswari saree and turban were weaved. It is said that Ahilya Bai herself designed first saree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://the13thstore.in/blogs/fabric-of-india/maheswari-saris-queen-attire|title=Maheswari Saris \u2013 Queen Attire|last=|first=|date=|website=THE 13th STORE|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref> These sarees were worn by female members of the royal court. These saris were also gifted to royal guests. You can easily see inspiration of designs in saris in local architecture. These [[cotton]] [[sari]]s are weaved with distinctive designs involving stripes, checks, and floral borders. \n\nTo save the local handloom industry [[Rehwa Society]], an [[NGO]] founded by the [[Holkar]]s, in 1979. This NGO gave women employment and revived the town's [[textile]]s.<ref>[http://www.rehwasociety.org/ Rehwa Society]</ref> About 130 weavers associated with the society produce over 100,000&nbsp;metres of fine fabrics a year. The weaving centre is located in one of Maheshwar's historic buildings. Rehwa Society also provides a free school for weavers' children and runs a low-cost health scheme. There are few other small local organisations involved in weaving of sarees and other fabrics.\n\nAhilya Fort which is now converted into a heritage hotel, founded by 'Maharajkumar Shrimant Shivaji Rao Holkar' (Prince Richard Holkar of Indore), a descendant of both [[Ahilyabai Holkar]] and the only son of [[Yeshwantrao Holkar II|M.Gen. HH Maharaja Shrimant Yeshwant Rao II Holkar of Indore]].<ref>[http://www.ahilyafort.com/ Ahilya Fort]</ref>\n\n==Festivals==\n[[File:Laxmi Bai kii Chhatri 02.jpg|right|thumb|Ghats on the banks of river Narmada]]\nMaheshwar is full of festivals and celebrations, some are:\nNag Panchami, Gudi Padava, Teez (New year celebrations according to the Hindu calendar), All Mondays of Shravan month, (DOLA of Kashivishwnath on last Monday, bhang is served as [[prasad]] of Shiva), Mahashivratri, Samoti Amavas, and all other Indian festivals. There are many visiting places like gold swing is also their and it is situated at Rajwada. Maheshwar also has the temple of Goddess Vindhyavasini Bhavani, one of the 24Shaktipeeths of Goddess Parvati.\n\nEvery year on the immediately preceding Sunday of Makar Sankranti (i.e. the Sunday just before the date when the Sun is about to enter the sign of Capricorn as per Indian Astrological / Sidereal calendar), Swaadhyaaya Bhavan Ashram (based at Mahalaxmi Nagar, Maheshwar) organizes [http://mahaamrityunjaya.blogspot.com Mahaamrityunjaya Rath Yaatraa] in the town of Maheshwar. This Mahaamrityunjaya Rath Yaatraa was initiated by Shri Harvilas Aasopaa for the welfare of humanity, and is known to be the first of its kind in the world. The yatra intends to invoke blessings of Ayurved Murti Bhagwaan Sadaashiv Mahaamrityunjaya (who is regarded as the primordial and supreme doctor), and it starts from Swaadhyaaya Bhawan Ashram and culminates at the banks of the holy river Narmada.\n\n== Film industry and Maheshwar ==\n[[File:Stay view from terrace west big.jpg|thumb|A scenic view of [[Narmada]] from top of the [[Ahilya (Hindu mythology)|Ahilya]] fort]]\nThe exquisite beauty of Maheshwar and river [[Narmada River|Narmada]] is captured in some [[Bollywood]] and [[Tamil language|Tamil]]/ [[Kollywood]] movies. Some of the movies shot in Maheshwar including the movie \"[[Asoka (2001 film)|Ashoka]]\", ''Tulsi'' (by actor and director Sachin), ''Mahashivratri'', [[A.R. Rehman|A R Rehman's]] music video, Tamil movie [[Alaipayuthey (film)|Alaipayuthey's]] song \"Snekithanea...\" and \" yaro yaro di...\" directed by Maniratnam, Tamil movie [[Leelai|Leelai's]] song \"Oru killi oru killi...\" directed by Andrew Vasanth Louis, [[Yuvan Shankar Raja|Yuvan Shankar Raja's]] musical Tamil movie [[Arrambam|Arrambam's]] song \"Adadada Arrambame...\" directed by [[Vishnuvardhan (director)|Vishnuvardhan]]. Also starting episodes of Zee TV serial [[Jhansi Ki Rani (2009 TV series)|Jhansi Ki Rani]] were shot here. In the 60's, Mythological film Mahashivratri's shooting was done here and many local artists were given a chance to act in that. Then Aadi Shankaryachary's shooting was completed in 1985. Many Film stars from [[Bharat Bhushan Bhalla|Bharat Bhushan]] to [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] have visited Maheshwar and admired its rich culture and beauty. Also Yamala Pagla Deewana (Dharmendra, Sunny Deol, Bobby Deol, Kulraj Randhawa come here for shooting) film's 50&nbsp;minute shot done here at Bazar Chowk, Rajwada, Ahilyabai Chhatri, Ahilya Ghaat, and many more location. The shooting of \"Radha Nachegi\" song from [[Tevar]] was done here. Also, recently few scenes of [[Bajirao Mastani]], [[Neerja]] and [[Gautamiputra Satakarni (film)]] were shot here. Recently the film [[Pad Man (film)|Pad Man]] directed by R.Balki starring Akshay Kumar, Sonam Kapoor, and Radhika Apte was shot here. And recently shot title track of Prabhu Deva directed, an Arbaz Khan production movie \"[[Dabangg 3]]\" starring \"Salman Khan\" was shot for 2 weaks. shooting of \"[[Kalank]]\" is also done here.\n\n== Culture ==\n\nMaheshwar is a culturally prosperous town and its importance is described in [[Purana]]s and through history. It is a religious town and people here are simple and pleasing.\n\n== Temples ==\n[[File:Chhatri of Vithoji 03.jpg|upright|thumb|Chhatri of [[Vithoji Rao Holkar|Vithoji]] in the Maheshwar Fort]]\n[[File:Fort of maheshwar1.jpg|thumb|Fort of Maheshwar]]\nIt is said that there are more than 100 temples in Maheshwar. it seems these temples are telling the long history of Maheshwar, most temples are spread along the right bank of the river near Maheshwar ghat and the vicinity of the fort.<ref>http://www.madhya-pradesh-tourism.com/tourist-attractions/maheshwar.html</ref>\n\n*SahastarArjun Temple near the holy river Narmada, Rajrajeshwar Mandir, Kashi Vishwanath Mandir, Chaturbhuj Narayan Mandir, Ahilya Mata's Chhatris, Chintamani Ganpati Mandir, Pandharinath Mandir, Bhawani Mata Mandir, Gobar Ganesh Mandir, Banke Bihari, Anant Narayan Mandir, [[Khedapati Hanuman]], Ram and Krishna Mandir and Narsingh Mandir. Kaleshwar and Jwaleshwar mandirs are located little far off. Baneshwar Mandir is located in a small island in the Narmada River.\n*Temple of [[Vindhyavasini]] Maheshwari, which is one of the [[Shakti Peeth]]s of Goddess Kali.\n*Sahastradhara is a place where Narmada River divides into several small streams and flows forcefully. An adventurous water sporting centre is being planned here.\n*'''Ek Mukhi Datta Temple''' is newly constructed temple in Sahastradhara, Jalkoti, Maheshwar.<ref name=\"dattadham.in\">http://dattadham.in</ref> It's also called \"'''Shiva Datta Dham'''\". This temple is constructed in 30&nbsp;acres of area. Temple area is approx 10000&nbsp;sq. feet. The temple is situated at the bank of historical Narmada River in its most serious, calm, adventured and horrible form. The main attraction in this temple is the very beautiful idols of Lord Ek Mukhi Datta, Maa Narmada and Lord Ganesha. Sadguru Shri Narayan Maharaj of Shri kshetra [[Narayanpur, Pune|Narayanpur]] (Anna) and his disciple are building \"Char DattaDhams\" in four different directions in India, of which 2 Dhams have already been completed.<ref>http://www.shreedattadham.com</ref><ref name=\"dattadham.in\"/>\n**First of the Char Dattadhams has been constructed in Madhya Pradesh \"[http://wikimapia.org/9852441/Shiv-Datta-Dham-Khargone-Maheshwar-Madhya-Pradesh Shiva Datta Dham, Jalkoti, Maheshwar, Khargone] Shiv Datta Dham, Jalkoti, Maheshwar, [[Madhya Pradesh]]\" \n**Second of the Char Dattadhams is in Kanyakumari [http://wikimapia.org/18609000/Anusaya-Datta-Dham Anusaya Datta Dham, Vattakottai, Kanyakumari]\"Anusaya Datta Dham, Vatta-kottai [[Vattakottai Fort]], Anju Gramam, [[Kanyakumari]]\". \n**Third of the Char Dattadhams is near Kolkata \"Bramha Datta Dham\" and it is under construction situated in [http://wikimapia.org/33291973/Bramha-Datta-Dham-Baruipara-Calcutta Bramha Datta Dham, Baruipara, Kolkata]\"Baruipara\". This will be the largest Hindu temple in West Bengal.\n**Shri Atri Dattadham, Himachal Pradesh\n\n==In pictures==\n<gallery>\nFile:Maheshwar Fort 04.jpg|Fort built by Mata Ahilyabai Holkar the ruler of Maheshwar Mandir at Maheshwar.\nFile:Royal Palace of Maheshwar.jpg|Royal Palace of Maheshwar.\nFile:Sunset view from Datta Temple,Jalkoti,Madhya Pradesh.jpg|Sunset view from Datta Temple, Jalkoti, [[Madhya Pradesh]].\nFile:Ek Mukhi Datta Temple,Sahastradhara,Jalkoti,Maheshwar.jpg|Ek Mukhi Datta Temple at Sahastradhara, Jalkoti\nFile:Art at Fort of Maheshwar.jpg|Art at Fort of Maheshwar\nFile:View of Narmada from fort of maheshwar.jpg|View of the Narmada from Fort of Maheshwar\nFile:Work at Maheshwar fort.jpg|Work at Maheshwar fort\nFile:MaheshwarFort.jpg|Maheshwar Fort\nFile:MaheshwarFort1.jpg|Maheshwar Fort\nFile:Work at maheshwar fort.jpg|Work at Maheshwar fort\nFile:ArtWork at Maheshwari fort.jpg|ArtWork at Maheshwari fort\nFile:Fort of Maheshwar.jpg|Fort of Maheshwar\nFile:Fort of maheshwar2.jpg|Fort of Maheshwar\nFile:Statue of Ahilybai Holkar, Maheshwar.jpg|Statue of Ahilybai Holkar, Maheshwar\nFile:Palace of holkar Maheshwar.jpg|Holkar palace, Maheshwar\nFile:Ahilyabai Holkar Statue in Maheshwar (1).jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==Cities near Maheshwar==\n[[Dhamnod]], [[Sendhwa]], [[Bagh, Dhar|Bagh]], [[Barwaha]], [[Barwani]], [[Sanawad]], [[Mundi]], [[Khargone]], [[Khandwa]], [[Mandleshwar]], [[Kasrawad]], [[Gogawan]], [[Mardana, Madhya Pradesh|Mardana]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Maratha Empire]]\n*[[List of Maratha dynasties and states]]\n*[[Indore State]]\n*[[Holkar]]\n*[[Mardana, Madhya Pradesh]]\n*[[Narmada Kothi (Maharajah of Indore Retreat Palace), Barwaha]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|http://maheshwar.in=}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Maheshwar}}\n* http://maheshwar.in\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/ch_maheshwar/sets/72157594583969585/ Photo Gallery of Maheshwar]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Maheshwar|short=x}}\n\n{{Indore Division}}\n{{Forts in Madhya Pradesh}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Khargone district]]\n[[Category:Khargone]]\n[[Category:Tourism in Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Former capital cities in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Maheshwar\n| other_name              = Mheysur <ref>https://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~292725~90063968:India-VI?sort=Pub_List_No_InitialSort%2CPub_Date%2CPub_List_No%2CSeries_No&qvq=q:Malwa;sort:Pub_List_No_InitialSort%2CPub_Date%2CPub_List_No%2CSeries_No;lc:RUMSEY~8~1&mi=0&trs=3</ref>\n| settlement_type         = Town\n| image_skyline           = Maheshwar 02.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = A street in Maheshwar\n| pushpin_map             = India Madhya Pradesh\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|22.11|N|75.35|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Madhya Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = Khargone\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 =\n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = 154\n| population_total        = 30000\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 451224\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 07283\n| registration_plate      = MP-10\n| website                 = {{URL|www.khargone.nic.in}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Maheshwar''' is a town in [[Khargone]] district of [[Madhya Pradesh]] state, in central [[India]]. It is located 13&nbsp;km east of National Highway 3 (Agra-Mumbai highway) and 91&nbsp;km from [[Indore]], the commercial capital of the state. The Town lies on the north bank of the [[Narmada River]].\nIt was the capital of the [[Malwa]] during the [[Maratha]] [[Holkar|Holkar reign]] till 6 January 1818, when the capital was shifted to [[Indore]] by Malhar Rao Holkar III.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word Maheshwar in Hindi means ''Great God, ''an epithet of [[Lord Shiva]].\n\n==History and mythology==\nWriters such as [[Hasmukh Dhirajlal Sankalia|HD Sankalia]],<ref>{{cite book |author=Hasmukhlal Dhirajlal Sankalia |title=Aspects of Indian History and Archaeology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2pwtAAAAMAAJ |year=1977 |publisher=B. R. |page=218 }}</ref> [[Pramatha Nath Bose|PN Bose]]<ref name=\"PNBose_1882\">{{cite book |author=PN Bose |publisher=Asiatic Society |location=Calcutta, India |title=Note on Mahishmati |work=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VVsyAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA129 |year=1882 |pages=129}}</ref> and [[Francis Wilford]],<ref name=\"PNBose_1882\"/> among others, identify Maheshwar as the ancient town of [[Mahishmati]].\n\nMaheshwar is believed to be built on the site of the ancient city of Somvanshya Shastrarjun Kshatriya, and was the capital of king [[Kartavirya Arjuna]], (Shree Shastrarjun) who is mentioned in the [[Sanskrit]] epics [[Ramayana]] and [[Mahabharata]]. According to a popular legend, one day the King Sahasrarjun and his 500 wives went to the river for a picnic. When the wives wanted a vast play area, the King stopped the mighty river Narmada with his 1000 arms. While they were all enjoying themselves, [[Ravana]] flew by in his Pushpak Vimana. Downstream, when he saw the dry river bed, he thought it was an ideal place to pray to Lord Shiva. He made a Shivalinga out of the sand and began to pray. When Sahasrajuna's wives were done playing and they stepped out of the river bed, he let the waters flow. The voluminous river flowed down sweeping Ravana's Shivalinga along, messing up his prayers. Furious, Ravana tracked Sahasrajuna and challenged him. Armed to the hilt the mighty Ravana was in for a huge surprise. The mighty Sahasrarjuna with the 1000 arms pinned Ravana to the ground. Then he placed 10 lamps on his heads and one on his hand. After tying up Ravana, Sahasrarjuna dragged him home and tied him up to the cradle pole of his son. A humiliated Ravana stayed prisoner until his release was secured. [[Jamadagni]] rishi, [[Renuka]] Devi and Lord [[Parashurama]] with whom Kartavirya Arjuna's story is closely associated also lived nearby.\n\nIn Mahabharata,<ref>[http://www.sacred-texts.com/hin/m02/m02030.htm story of Mahishmati in Mahabharata]</ref> there is a narration of an unusual tradition wherein marriage as a civil institution was not universal in Mahishmati unlike in rest of Aryavarta, which is also narrated in the Telugu-language ''[[Andhra Mahabharatam|Andhra Mahabharata]]'' in \u2018Sabha parva\u2019.\n\nAs per the legend, there was a Nishada king named Nila who ruled over Mahishmati. King Nila had a daughter who was exceedingly beautiful. So much so that [[Agni]] (lord of fire) fell in love with her which was reciprocated. The princess always used to stay near the sacred fire of her father, causing it to blaze up with vigour. And king Nila's sacred fire, even if fanned, would not blaze until agitated by the gentle breath of her lips. Agni, assuming the form of a [[Brahman (cattle)|Brahman]] starts courting with the princess for long. But, one day the couple was discovered by the king, who became furious. Nila thereupon ordered the Brahman to be punished according to law. At this the illustrious deity flamed up in wrath and beholding the terrible flame, the king felt terrified and bent his head low on the ground. King hails Lord Agni and says he cannot punish a god who is responsible for the origin of Vedas, source of all Knowledge and Dharma. Pacified Agni then grants a boon to Nishada, and the King requests for the protection of his kingdom from any invasions. Agni swears to protect his kingdom on the condition that the king should sanctify pleasure out of pure love a legitimate action in his kingdom. Liberated from the orthodoxy of marriage as a prelude, women of Mahishmati enjoyed freedom that was then unheard of elsewhere in Arya-Varta.\n\nYears later, after the epic war the victorious [[Yudhishthira]] plans on conducting a [[Yagna]] by winning over everyone else on Earth. [[Sahadeva]], the youngest of Pandavas knowing that Lord Agni was protecting the Nishada kingdom, prays to Lord Agni successfully and there upon moves to [[Saurashtra people|Saurashtra]] kingdom.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Andhra Mahabharatha|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>{{page needed|date=May 2016}}\n\nOf note, even to this day, the Sahasrarjun temple at Maheshwar lights 11 lamps in honour of Lord Agni blessing the Kingdom. Alternatively, this tradition is attributed to Sahasrarjun queens humiliating captive ten-headed Ravana by lighting up candles on his foreheads.\n\nIn the late eighteenth century, Maheshwar served as the capital of the great [[Maratha]] queen [[Rajmata Ahilya Devi Holkar]]. She embellished the city with many buildings and public works, and it is home to her palace, as well as numerous temples, a [[fort]], and riverfront ''ghats'' (broad stone steps which step down to the river).\n\nJagadguru Kripaluji Maharaj has performed various akhand (continues) sankirtan outside the Shiva temple at Maheshwar for more than months. Even though Kripaluji was from mahu (30&nbsp;km from Maheshwar), he frequently visited this place in his early life with devotees of lord Krishna to perform sankirtan on the banks of the Narmada river in Maheshwar.\n\n[[File:Maheshwar Fort - Exterior 03.jpg|thumb|left|Fort Ahilya of the [[Holkar]] dynasty, in Maheshwar.]]\n[[File:Maheshwar fort.JPG|thumb|right|Ahilya Fort at Maheshwar.]]\n[[File:Narmada river, Maheshwari.jpg|thumb|Narmada river, Maheshwari]]\n[[File:Fort of maheshwar.jpg|thumb|Fort of Maheshwar and Narmada river]]\n\n==Demographics==\n{{As of|2001}} India [[census]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Maheshwar had a population of 24000. Males constitute 51% of the population and females 49%. Maheshwar has an average literacy rate of 67%, higher than the national average of 59.5%: male literacy is 75%, and female literacy is 59%. In Maheshwar, 14% of the population is under 6&nbsp;years of age.\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Religion in Maheshwar \n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|left1=Religion\n|right1=Percent\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|orange|77.86}}\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|green|20.70}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism|Jains]]|pink|0.91}}\n{{bar percent|[[Sikh]]s |red|0.35}}\n{{bar percent|Others\u2020|black|0.2}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|blue|0.11}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions<br />\n\u2020<small>Includes [[Buddhism|Buddhists]] (0.2%).</small>\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:PC080025.JPG|right|180px|thumb|Maheshwari sari laced with bright ''[[Zari]]'' ([[brocade]])]]\n[[File:Looms at Rehwa society, Maheshwari handloom sarees weavers society, Maheshwar.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Looms at Rehwa society, Maheshwari handloom sarees weavers society, Maheshwar.]]Maheshwar has been a centre of handloom [[weaving]] since the 5th century. Maheshwar is the home of one of India's finest handloom fabric traditions. It is noted as a centre for weaving colourful Maheshwari sarees.<ref>[http://www.qohindia.com/collections/all/maheshwari Maheshwari Sarees]</ref> It rose to popularity under the rule of strong maratha leader Queen [[Ahilyabai Holkar|Devi Ahilya Bai Holkar]]. Ahilya Bai wanted royal gifts for the royal guest. Hence weavers from Mandu and Surat were hired and Maheswari saree and turban were weaved. It is said that Ahilya Bai herself designed first saree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://the13thstore.in/blogs/fabric-of-india/maheswari-saris-queen-attire|title=Maheswari Saris \u2013 Queen Attire|last=|first=|date=|website=THE 13th STORE|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref> These sarees were worn by female members of the royal court. These saris were also gifted to royal guests. You can easily see inspiration of designs in saris in local architecture. These [[cotton]] [[sari]]s are weaved with distinctive designs involving stripes, checks, and floral borders. \n\nTo save the local handloom industry [[Rehwa Society]], an [[NGO]] founded by the [[Holkar]]s, in 1979. This NGO gave women employment and revived the town's [[textile]]s.<ref>[http://www.rehwasociety.org/ Rehwa Society]</ref> About 130 weavers associated with the society produce over 100,000&nbsp;metres of fine fabrics a year. The weaving centre is located in one of Maheshwar's historic buildings. Rehwa Society also provides a free school for weavers' children and runs a low-cost health scheme. There are few other small local organisations involved in weaving of sarees and other fabrics.\n\nAhilya Fort which is now converted into a heritage hotel, founded by 'Maharajkumar Shrimant Shivaji Rao Holkar' (Prince Richard Holkar of Indore), a descendant of both [[Ahilyabai Holkar]] and the only son of [[Yeshwantrao Holkar II|M.Gen. HH Maharaja Shrimant Yeshwant Rao II Holkar of Indore]].<ref>[http://www.ahilyafort.com/ Ahilya Fort]</ref>\n\n==Festivals==\n[[File:Laxmi Bai kii Chhatri 02.jpg|right|thumb|Ghats on the banks of river Narmada]]\nMaheshwar is full of festivals and celebrations, some are:\nNag Panchami, Gudi Padava, Teez (New year celebrations according to the Hindu calendar), All Mondays of Shravan month, (DOLA of Kashivishwnath on last Monday, bhang is served as [[prasad]] of Shiva), Mahashivratri, Samoti Amavas, and all other Indian festivals. There are many visiting places like gold swing is also their and it is situated at Rajwada. Maheshwar also has the temple of Goddess Vindhyavasini Bhavani, one of the 24Shaktipeeths of Goddess Parvati.\n\nEvery year on the immediately preceding Sunday of Makar Sankranti (i.e. the Sunday just before the date when the Sun is about to enter the sign of Capricorn as per Indian Astrological / Sidereal calendar), Swaadhyaaya Bhavan Ashram (based at Mahalaxmi Nagar, Maheshwar) organizes [http://mahaamrityunjaya.blogspot.com Mahaamrityunjaya Rath Yaatraa] in the town of Maheshwar. This Mahaamrityunjaya Rath Yaatraa was initiated by Shri Harvilas Aasopaa for the welfare of humanity, and is known to be the first of its kind in the world. The yatra intends to invoke blessings of Ayurved Murti Bhagwaan Sadaashiv Mahaamrityunjaya (who is regarded as the primordial and supreme doctor), and it starts from Swaadhyaaya Bhawan Ashram and culminates at the banks of the holy river Narmada.\n\n== Film industry and Maheshwar ==\n[[File:Stay view from terrace west big.jpg|thumb|A scenic view of [[Narmada]] from top of the [[Ahilya (Hindu mythology)|Ahilya]] fort]]\nThe exquisite beauty of Maheshwar and river [[Narmada River|Narmada]] is captured in some [[Bollywood]] and [[Tamil language|Tamil]]/ [[Kollywood]] movies. Some of the movies shot in Maheshwar including the movie \"[[Asoka (2001 film)|Ashoka]]\", ''Tulsi'' (by actor and director Sachin), ''Mahashivratri'', [[A.R. Rehman|A R Rehman's]] music video, Tamil movie [[Alaipayuthey (film)|Alaipayuthey's]] song \"Snekithanea...\" and \" yaro yaro di...\" directed by Maniratnam, Tamil movie [[Leelai|Leelai's]] song \"Oru killi oru killi...\" directed by Andrew Vasanth Louis, [[Yuvan Shankar Raja|Yuvan Shankar Raja's]] musical Tamil movie [[Arrambam|Arrambam's]] song \"Adadada Arrambame...\" directed by [[Vishnuvardhan (director)|Vishnuvardhan]]. Also starting episodes of Zee TV serial [[Jhansi Ki Rani (2009 TV series)|Jhansi Ki Rani]] were shot here. In the 60's, Mythological film Mahashivratri's shooting was done here and many local artists were given a chance to act in that. Then Aadi Shankaryachary's shooting was completed in 1985. Many Film stars from [[Bharat Bhushan Bhalla|Bharat Bhushan]] to [[Shah Rukh Khan|Shahrukh Khan]] have visited Maheshwar and admired its rich culture and beauty. Also Yamala Pagla Deewana (Dharmendra, Sunny Deol, Bobby Deol, Kulraj Randhawa come here for shooting) film's 50&nbsp;minute shot done here at Bazar Chowk, Rajwada, Ahilyabai Chhatri, Ahilya Ghaat, and many more location. The shooting of \"Radha Nachegi\" song from [[Tevar]] was done here. Also, recently few scenes of [[Bajirao Mastani]], [[Neerja]] and [[Gautamiputra Satakarni (film)]] were shot here. Recently the film [[Pad Man (film)|Pad Man]] directed by R.Balki starring Akshay Kumar, Sonam Kapoor, and Radhika Apte was shot here. And recently shot title track of Prabhu Deva directed, an Arbaz Khan production movie \"[[Dabangg 3]]\" starring \"Salman Khan\" was shot for 2 weaks. shooting of \"[[Kalank]]\" is also done here.\n\n== Culture ==\n\nMaheshwar is a culturally prosperous town and its importance is described in [[Purana]]s and through history. It is a religious town and people here are simple and pleasing.\n\n== Temples ==\n[[File:Chhatri of Vithoji 03.jpg|upright|thumb|Chhatri of [[Vithoji Rao Holkar|Vithoji]] in the Maheshwar Fort]]\n[[File:Fort of maheshwar1.jpg|thumb|Fort of Maheshwar]]\nIt is said that there are more than 100 temples in Maheshwar. it seems these temples are telling the long history of Maheshwar, most temples are spread along the right bank of the river near Maheshwar ghat and the vicinity of the fort.<ref>http://www.madhya-pradesh-tourism.com/tourist-attractions/maheshwar.html</ref>\n\n*SahastarArjun Temple near the holy river Narmada, Rajrajeshwar Mandir, Kashi Vishwanath Mandir, Chaturbhuj Narayan Mandir, Ahilya Mata's Chhatris, Chintamani Ganpati Mandir, Pandharinath Mandir, Bhawani Mata Mandir, Gobar Ganesh Mandir, Banke Bihari, Anant Narayan Mandir, [[Khedapati Hanuman]], Ram and Krishna Mandir and Narsingh Mandir. Kaleshwar and Jwaleshwar mandirs are located little far off. Baneshwar Mandir is located in a small island in the Narmada River.\n*Temple of [[Vindhyavasini]] Maheshwari, which is one of the [[Shakti Peeth]]s of Goddess Kali.\n*Sahastradhara is a place where Narmada River divides into several small streams and flows forcefully. An adventurous water sporting centre is being planned here.\n*'''Ek Mukhi Datta Temple''' is newly constructed temple in Sahastradhara, Jalkoti, Maheshwar.<ref name=\"dattadham.in\">http://dattadham.in</ref> It's also called \"'''Shiva Datta Dham'''\". This temple is constructed in 30&nbsp;acres of area. Temple area is approx 10000&nbsp;sq. feet. The temple is situated at the bank of historical Narmada River in its most serious, calm, adventured and horrible form. The main attraction in this temple is the very beautiful idols of Lord Ek Mukhi Datta, Maa Narmada and Lord Ganesha. Sadguru Shri Narayan Maharaj of Shri kshetra [[Narayanpur, Pune|Narayanpur]] (Anna) and his disciple are building \"Char DattaDhams\" in four different directions in India, of which 2 Dhams have already been completed.<ref>http://www.shreedattadham.com</ref><ref name=\"dattadham.in\"/>\n**First of the Char Dattadhams has been constructed in Madhya Pradesh \"[http://wikimapia.org/9852441/Shiv-Datta-Dham-Khargone-Maheshwar-Madhya-Pradesh Shiva Datta Dham, Jalkoti, Maheshwar, Khargone] Shiv Datta Dham, Jalkoti, Maheshwar, [[Madhya Pradesh]]\" \n**Second of the Char Dattadhams is in Kanyakumari [http://wikimapia.org/18609000/Anusaya-Datta-Dham Anusaya Datta Dham, Vattakottai, Kanyakumari]\"Anusaya Datta Dham, Vatta-kottai [[Vattakottai Fort]], Anju Gramam, [[Kanyakumari]]\". \n**Third of the Char Dattadhams is near Kolkata \"Bramha Datta Dham\" and it is under construction situated in [http://wikimapia.org/33291973/Bramha-Datta-Dham-Baruipara-Calcutta Bramha Datta Dham, Baruipara, Kolkata]\"Baruipara\". This will be the largest Hindu temple in West Bengal.\n**Shri Atri Dattadham, Himachal Pradesh\n\n==In pictures==\n<gallery>\nFile:Maheshwar Fort 04.jpg|Fort built by Mata Ahilyabai Holkar the ruler of Maheshwar Mandir at Maheshwar.\nFile:Royal Palace of Maheshwar.jpg|Royal Palace of Maheshwar.\nFile:Sunset view from Datta Temple,Jalkoti,Madhya Pradesh.jpg|Sunset view from Datta Temple, Jalkoti, [[Madhya Pradesh]].\nFile:Ek Mukhi Datta Temple,Sahastradhara,Jalkoti,Maheshwar.jpg|Ek Mukhi Datta Temple at Sahastradhara, Jalkoti\nFile:Art at Fort of Maheshwar.jpg|Art at Fort of Maheshwar\nFile:View of Narmada from fort of maheshwar.jpg|View of the Narmada from Fort of Maheshwar\nFile:Work at Maheshwar fort.jpg|Work at Maheshwar fort\nFile:MaheshwarFort.jpg|Maheshwar Fort\nFile:MaheshwarFort1.jpg|Maheshwar Fort\nFile:Work at maheshwar fort.jpg|Work at Maheshwar fort\nFile:ArtWork at Maheshwari fort.jpg|ArtWork at Maheshwari fort\nFile:Fort of Maheshwar.jpg|Fort of Maheshwar\nFile:Fort of maheshwar2.jpg|Fort of Maheshwar\nFile:Statue of Ahilybai Holkar, Maheshwar.jpg|Statue of Ahilybai Holkar, Maheshwar\nFile:Palace of holkar Maheshwar.jpg|Holkar palace, Maheshwar\nFile:Ahilyabai Holkar Statue in Maheshwar (1).jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==Cities near Maheshwar==\n[[Dhamnod]], [[Sendhwa]], [[Bagh, Dhar|Bagh]], [[Barwaha]], [[Barwani]], [[Sanawad]], [[Mundi]], [[Khargone]], [[Khandwa]], [[Mandleshwar]], [[Kasrawad]], [[Gogawan]], [[Mardana, Madhya Pradesh|Mardana]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Maratha Empire]]\n*[[List of Maratha dynasties and states]]\n*[[Indore State]]\n*[[Holkar]]\n*[[Mardana, Madhya Pradesh]]\n*[[Narmada Kothi (Maharajah of Indore Retreat Palace), Barwaha]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|http://maheshwar.in=}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Maheshwar}}\n* http://maheshwar.in\n* [https://www.flickr.com/photos/ch_maheshwar/sets/72157594583969585/ Photo Gallery of Maheshwar]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Maheshwar|short=x}}\n\n{{Indore Division}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Khargone district]]\n[[Category:Khargone]]\n[[Category:Tourism in Madhya Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Former capital cities in India]]\n", "name_user": "Premeditated Chaos", "label": "safe", "comment": "+navbox (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maheshwar"}
{"title_page": "2001 UEFA Regions' Cup", "text_new": "{{Infobox international football competition\n| tourney_name = UEFA Regions' Cup\n| year = 2001\n| other_titles = UEFA Regions' Cup Czech Republic 2001\n| image = \n| size =\n| caption =\n| country = Czech Republic\n| dates = 18 June &ndash; 24 June \n| num_teams = 8\n| confederations =\n| venues =\n| cities =\n| champion_other = {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Moravian\u2013Silesian Football League|Moravia]]\n| count = 1\n| second_other = {{flagicon|POR}} [[Braga Football Association|Braga]]\n| third_other =\n| fourth_other =\n| matches =\n| goals =\n| attendance =\n| top_scorer =\n| updated =\n}}\nThe '''2001 UEFA Regions' Cup''' was the second [[UEFA Regions' Cup]]. It was held in the [[Czech Republic]] and won by the ''[[Moravian\u2013Silesian Football League|Moravia]]'' team from the host nation, which beat [[Portugal]]'s ''[[Braga Football Association|Braga]]'' 4&ndash;2 on [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalties]], after drawing 2&ndash;2 after [[extra time]], in the final.\n\n== Preliminary round ==\nThe 35 teams entered were drawn into eight groups of four and one group of three, with the following countries hosting each group's matches:\n:Group 1 &ndash; {{flag|Bulgaria}}\n:Group 2 &ndash; {{flag|Czech Republic}}\n:Group 3 &ndash; {{flag|Finland}}\n:Group 4 &ndash; {{flag|France}}\n:Group 5 &ndash; {{flag|Luxembourg}}\n:Group 6 &ndash; {{flag|Malta}}\n:Group 7 &ndash; {{flag|Russia}}\n:Group 8 &ndash; {{flag|San Marino}}\n:Group 9 &ndash; {{flag|Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\nSeven group winners automatically qualified for the final tournament, with the two \"worst winners\" playing against each other in a [[playoff]] for the remaining place.\n\n=== Group 1 ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"Goals for\" |GF\n!width=20 abbr=\"Goals against\" |GA\n!width=20 abbr=\"Goal difference\" |GD\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|- bgcolor=#ccffcc\n|align=left|{{flagicon|BUL}} [[Plovdiv Province|Plovdiv]]\n|3||2||1||0||7||4||+3||'''7'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|UKR}} [[FC Dnister Ovidiopol|Dnister]]\n|3||2||1||0||6||3||+3||'''7'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|SVK}} [[3. Liga (Slovakia)|East]]\n|3||1||0||2||3||5||&minus;2||'''3'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon image|FLAG-Veszpr%C3%A9m-megye.svg}} [[Veszpr\u00e9m County|Bakony]]\n|3||0||0||3||3||7||&minus;4||'''0'''\n|}\n\n{|width=100% cellspacing=1\n!width=25%|\n!width=10%|\n!\n|-\n|22 October 2000\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|'''Odessa'''||align=center|'''2 &ndash; 1'''||'''East'''\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|'''Plovdiv'''||align=center|'''3 &ndash; 2'''||'''Bakony'''\n|-\n|24 October 2000\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|'''Bakony'''||align=center|'''0 &ndash; 2'''||'''Odessa'''\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|'''East'''||align=center|'''0 &ndash; 2'''||'''Plovdiv'''\n|-\n|26 October 2000\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|'''East'''||align=center|'''2 &ndash; 1'''||'''Bakony'''\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|'''Odessa'''||align=center|'''2 &ndash; 2'''||'''Plovdiv'''\n|}\n\n=== Group 2 ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"Goals for\" |GF\n!width=20 abbr=\"Goals against\" |GA\n!width=20 abbr=\"Goal difference\" |GD\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|- bgcolor=#ccffcc\n|align=left|{{flagicon image|Banner_of_arms_of_Moravia.svg}} [[Moravian\u2013Silesian Football League|Moravia]]\n|3||3||0||0||12||2||+10||'''9'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|LVA}} [[Latvian Football Federation|Latvia]]\n|3||2||0||1||6||4||+2||'''6'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon image|Flagge-Chisinau-01-11_(Flagge).png}} [[Chi\u015fin\u0103u]]\n|3||0||1||2||0||3||&minus;3||'''1'''\n|